metadata.name: fields, wireframes #10
metadata.description:
The second part of our generative sketchbook of ideas for a sculpture garden.

Fields builds off Stan Allen's seminal essay "Field Conditions" in which he laid out a prototypical theory of architectural field schemes. Field Conditions are opposed to figural or object-based compositional strategies and approach a site from a systemic point of view. These fields contain a range of possible wall-types. Some produce enclosures, while others dictate a wandering path.

Built with p5.js
By office ca
2022

metadata.name: Horizons #60
metadata.description: About fifteen years ago (in 2006), I went to see an exhibition of photographs by Hiroshi Sugimoto at the Hirshhorn in Washington DC. I was transfixed. I’d spent the first part of the morning in the East Wing of the National Gallery, gazing into the depths of Rothko’s blues. Somehow the Sugimoto “Seascapes” felt the same. A magical illusion of endless depth performed on the surface of an image. I remember that they were displayed in a dark room. The walls were painted slate grey and the light were off. The photographs were printed on some sort of translucent material and lit from behind. I understood the technical aspects of Hiroshi’s craft. How he experimented with exposure lengths to move the image from representational to abstract. This reminded me of my Polaroid camera and how I’d come to favor the ones that turned out looking more like paintings than photographs. “Horizons” tries to recapture all of these feelings. In full saturation. Multiple exposures burning a composition onto the backlit screen.

metadata.name: Mystery Blobs #12
metadata.description: A generative neural network based on the SIREN architecture is trained to try and match a text prompt featuring 'Mysterious orbs...'. These are the results, running as WebGL shaders. With nothing but sine waves a few learned weights, the network does its best to please.

metadata.name: David #6
metadata.description:
Oh David!

Need I introduce him?

The Biblical hero. The symbol of strength and youthful beauty. The size.

He was supposedly gazing at the direction of the Medici family. We gaze at him.

We measure him with laser scanners in the Digital Michelangelo Project. And as Guan Xiao sang in her David (2013) at Biennale di Venezia (2017), we study him, shoot him, sing for him, sculpture him, draw him, reproduce him.

His eyes. His gaze. His view point.

Does it give me power if I arrange him, rotate him, and color him?

Does it give me power to go inside his head and look outwards?

metadata.name: BLEND #52
metadata.description:
Blend are generative loops and animated pieces creating a shape with a digital painting effect.
The size, position and motion frequency of trails are generated for each token, along with the color theme. 
You can press spacebar to stop the animation.

Created by Quentin Hocdé, in Brussels (Belgium).  

Features :
	- Between 10 and 80 trails, impacted or not by an update of their radius and randomly filled
	- 4 directions - from North West (NW), from North East (NE), from North or from West.
	- Duration between 16 and 24 seconds
	- Amplitude of the shape on X and Y
	- Offset delay: between 0.1 and trails count, manage the delay between each trails movement
	- Noise count : number of points to create the noise effect on background
	- Background color :  color randomly get from 1 of 151 color themes

metadata.name: Coronavirus Genome Sequence #11
metadata.description:
This is a visual representation of the coronavirus genome sequence. 

The genome sequence consists of 4 different nucleotides - A, T, G, and C.

For each nucleotide a circle is drawn. The type will determine what color the circle is and in what direction the sequence evolves.

Color palette and direction-change is dependent on the hash.
